a2dbee77-3d4f-41dc-bd8a-9382a63be792.17b68306-eeaf-422a-a8b7-e41b009bdd4a.description=Releases a lock with an id given by the value of the lockId input. 
Inputs\:
   lockId - the id of the lock, maximum 255 characters.

Responses\:
   success - the only response returned.

Results\:
   there are no results.

Notes\:
1) The operation only releases locks acquired by the current run. 
   It cannot release another run's locks.

2) The operation succeeds whether or not there is a lock held 
   by the current run with the supplied id.
a2dbee77-3d4f-41dc-bd8a-9382a63be792.27a70216-e50c-435b-bedf-78e99fed1336.prompt=HostName\: a2dbee77-3d4f-41dc-bd8a-9382a63be792.30f22ac0-6301-4b90-88bf-a10a7535fd64.description=
This operation adds a flow variable to the local context. The variable is available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:
    keyName - The name of the flow variable to add.
    myValue - The value to assign to the flow variable.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of "myValue" input field.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

Note\:
   If a flow variable with the same name already exists, its value will be overwritten.
a2dbee77-3d4f-41dc-bd8a-9382a63be792.340b1e59-cf50-40d8-b550-eaf4c3aeb307.prompt=HostName\: a2dbee77-3d4f-41dc-bd8a-9382a63be792.73886e5f-aba8-471f-ac8a-e82d49634428.description=This operation runs a SQL command. Inputs\: DBServerName - The hostname or ip address of the database server. DbType - The type of database to connect to. Valid values\: Oracle, MSSQL, Sybase, Netcool, DB2 and Custom. Default value\: Oracle Username - The username to use when connecting to the database. Password - The password to use when connecting to the database. instance - The name instance (for MSSQL Server). Leave it blank for default instance. DbPort - The port to connect to. Default values\: Oracle\: 1521, MSSQL\: 1433, Sybase\: 5000, Netcool\: 4100, DB2\: 50000. Database - The name of the database. authenticationType - The type of authentication used to access the database (applicable only to MSSQL type). Valid values\: sql, windows (for MSSQL) Default value\: sql dbClass - The classname of the JDBC driver to use. dbURL - The url required to load up the driver and make your connection. Command - The command to execute. timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution. When the default value is used, there is no limit on the amount of time allowed for a running command to complete. Default value\: 0 databasePoolingProperties - Properties for database pooling configuration. This parameter replaces the databasePooling.properties file from 9x version (you may copy-paste the file content here). Pooling is disabled by default. For more details check the /Library/Operations/Database/JDBC folder description. Example\: db.pooling.enable\=true resultSetType - the result set type. See JDBC folder description for more details. Valid values\: TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY, TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE,TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE. Default value\: TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY resultSetConcurrency - the result set concurrency. See JDBC folder description for more details. Valid values\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY, CONCUR_UPDATABLE Default value\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the "Command completed successfully" message if the operation succeeded, or a failure message otherwise. outputText - The return result of SQL command. updateCount - The update count of the command executed. Responses\: success - The command was executed successfully. failure - Failed to execute the command. Note\: 1. Check the JDBC folder description for details on how to load database connectors. 2. In case of using subprograms like (GET_LINE, GET_LINES, NEW_LINE, PUT, PUT_LUNE) from DBMS_OUTPUT package, the DBMS_OUTPUT.ENABLE() declaration should be used before of these calls. a2dbee77-3d4f-41dc-bd8a-9382a63be792.78a09fb5-824b-43a0-84d1-0e0c3990b4fa.description=
This operation runs a SQL SELECT query.
The first row is returned on the first run of the operation.
Subsequent calls with the same information will return the other rows.

Inputs\:
    DBServerName - The hostname or ip address of the database server.
    DbType - The type of database to connect to. 
Valid values\: Oracle, MSSQL, Sybase, Netcool, DB2 and Custom.
Default value\: Oracle
    Username - The username to use when connecting to the server.
    Password - The password to use when connecting to the server.
    instance - The name instance of MSSQL Server. Leave it blank for default instance.
Example\: MSSQLSERVER
    DbPort - The port to connect to.
Valid values\: Oracle\: 1521, MSSQL\: 1433, Sybase\: 5000, Netcool\: 4100, DB2\: 50000.
    Database - The name of the database to connect to.
    authenticationType - The type of authentication used to access the database (applicable only to MSSQL type). 
Valid values\: sql, windows (for MSSQL)
default value\: sql
    dbClass - The class name of the JDBC driver to use.
    dbURL - The URL required to load up the driver and make your connection.
    Command - The SQL query to execute.
    Delimiter - The delimiter to use between resulted values in "returnResult" and column names in "columnNames".
    Key - The key to help keep multiple query results distinct.
    timeout - Seconds to wait before timing out the SQL command execution. When the default value is used, there is no limit on the amount of time allowed for a running command to complete.
Default values\: 0 
    databasePoolingProperties - Properties for database pooling configuration. This parameter replaces the databasePooling.properties file from 9x version (you may copy-paste the file content here). Pooling is disabled by default. For more details check the /Library/Operations/Database/JDBC folder description.
Example\: db.pooling.enable\=true
    resultSetType - the result set type. See JDBC folder description for more details.
Valid values\: TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY, TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE,TYPE_SCROLL_SENSITIVE.
Default value\: TYPE_SCROLL_INSENSITIVE except DB2 which is overridden to TYPE_FORWARD_ONLY
    resultSetConcurrency - the result set concurrency. See JDBC folder description for more details.
Valid values\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY, CONCUR_UPDATABLE
Default value\: CONCUR_READ_ONLY
    ignoreCase - If set to true the inputs' letters case will be ignored and converted to lowercase.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: true

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the data of one row, separated by the "Delimiter". 
    columnNames - The names of all the columns returned, separated by the "Delimiter".
    rowsLeft - The number of remaining rows that match the query.

Responses\:
    more items - More rows are available for retrieval.
    no more items - No more rows are available.
    failure - Failed to execute the command.

Notes\: 
1. SQL statement other than SELECT statement (like INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE) is not supported. In case statements other than SELECT are executed then the operation will fail but the statements might get partially or fully executed in the database.
2. If the column type is "ntext", the "returnResult" returns the name of the JDBC driver instead of the actual column value. In this case, use the "SQL Query LOB" operation instead.

Note\:
    Check the JDBC folder description for details on how to load database connectors.

Responses\:

2) The operation succeeds whether or not there is a lock held

a2dbee77-3d4f-41dc-bd8a-9382a63be792.d766b18e-fd95-474b-b845-c48447beb271.description=Attempts to acquire the specified lock, and sleeps until the lock is available. 
Inputs\:
   lockId - the id of the lock, maximum 255 characters.
   timeout - The maximum number of seconds this flow will run for.
  seconds - The number of seconds to sleep for between each attempt at acquiring the lock.

Responses\:
   success - if the lock has been successfully acquired.
   failure - if the lock could not be acquired.

Result\:
   Code - 0 if the operation succeeds, 1 otherwise.

Notes\:
1) The locks acquired by this operation are not reentrant. This means that 
   once a lock is acquired by a run, all subsequent attempts at acquiring 
   the same lock by the same run (or any other run) will fail.

2) Once a run terminates, all the locks that were acquired during its execution
   are automatically released.
